Elliotte Rusty Harold wrote:
&gt; import junit.framework.*;
&gt; import junit.textui.TestRunner;
&gt; 
&gt; public class DataDrivenTest extends TestCase{
&gt; 
&gt;      int i;
&gt; 
&gt;      public DataDrivenTest(int i) {
&gt;          this.i = i;
&gt;      }
&gt; 
&gt;      public static Test suite() {
&gt;          TestSuite result = new TestSuite();
&gt;          result.addTest(new DataDrivenTest(1));
&gt;          result.addTest(new DataDrivenTest(2));
&gt;          return result;
&gt;      }
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt;      public void testFoo() {
&gt;          assertTrue(i &gt; 0);
&gt;      }
&gt; 
&gt;      public static void main(String[] args) {
&gt;        TestRunner.run(suite());
&gt;      }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Typical output is:
&gt; .F.F
&gt; Time: 0.025
&gt; There were 2 failures:
&gt; 1) null(DataDrivenTest)junit.framework.AssertionFailedError
&gt;       at DataDrivenTest.main(DataDrivenTest.java:25)
&gt; 2) null(DataDrivenTest)junit.framework.AssertionFailedError
&gt;       at DataDrivenTest.main(DataDrivenTest.java:25)
&gt; 
&gt; FAILURES!!!
&gt; Tests run: 2,  Failures: 2,  Errors: 0
&gt; 
&gt; What am I missing? Why does this fail?

runTest() wants to use the name of the test case to look up the test 
method by reflection then invoke it. Right now, the name is null.

I usually set the name to something descriptive, often including the 
test data for that test. I then implement runTest() with the code you 
have in testFoo().
